article.description:
Playing without star guard Jackie Stiles
and two other perimeter players on the court with injuries, the
Portland Fire went inside to end their 10-month losing streak.
article.headline: Fire earn first win since last July
article.linkText: Fire end 14-game losing streak without injured Stiles
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Playing without star guard Jackie Stiles and two other perimeter players on the court with injuries, the Portland Fire went inside to end their 10-month losing streak. Sylvia Crawley and Alisa Burras scored 14 points and Kristin Folkl added 13 to lead the Fire to their first victory since July 24 of last year, 86-73 over the Sacramento Monarchs on Thursday night, snapping a 14-game skid. Tamicha Jackson had a stellar game at point guard for the Fire (1-4), with 15 points and eight assists. Jackson started at point while regular Ukari Figgs -- still bothered by dental injuries suffered in a collision with Stiles on Sunday -- started at shooting guard. "This kid is the kind of kid that every team wants to have,'' said Portland coach Linda Hargrove of Jackson. "She's so explosive and so quick, I think she's the quickest player in the WNBA.'' But it was the post play of Burras, Crawley and Folkl that dug Portland out of an early 10-point deficit. "I like our post rotation,'' Hargrove said. "I like the athleticism of Sylvia and DeMya (Walker) and Kristin, and the power of Burras.'' Burras leads the league in field-goal percentage at 71 percent. "I'm just taking advantage of what they give me. When you have guards like (Jackson) and Ukari that can find you in the right places, it makes my job a lot easier.'' Burras and Folkl each had seven rebounds for the Fire and Crawley had five. Portland outrebounded Sacramento 35-20 and shot a season-high 47.6 percent from the floor. Reserve Ruthie Bolton led the Monarchs (0-2) with 21 points, while Kedra Holland-Corn scored 16 and La'Keshia Frett added 12. Both teams were short-handed. Portland was without Stiles, who missed her second straight game with bursitis in her right heel and LaQuanda Barksdale played only three minutes with a fractured left middle finger. Sacramento was missing center Kara Wolters who sat out with a sprained right ankle and star forward Yolanda Griffith is on the injured list. "We came out a little flat for the second half,'' Bolton said. "A sign of a great team is you can win without your star. We could have done better with what we had.'' The Monarchs went on an 11-0 run to take a 17-7 lead, thanks in large part to poor shooting by Portland. But the Fire responded with a 13-3 run to get back in it midway through the first half. Portland closed the half on a 12-2 run to take a 41-38 lead. Portland led by as many as 17 and the closest the Monarchs got was seven with 1:57 remaining. Portland guard Tully Bevilaqua returned after missing training camp and the first four games of the season while fulfilling commitments with a professional team in Hungary. The Rose Garden crowd of 6,441 gave the veteran a standing ovation when she entered the game. Game notes
Portland native Vecepia Towery, who won the latest edition of "Survivor,'' was in attendance. Towery, who played basketball in Europe during her military career, was in town to see her family before embarking on a nationwide "Survivor'' tour and was honored at halftime. ... To make room for Bevilaqua, Portland placed guard Carolyn Young and forward Amber Hall on the injured list, both suffering from right patella tendinitis, and waived guard Marla Brumfield. The Fire also activated center Jenny Mowe from the injured list. ... Portland improved to 2-5 all-time against Sacramento.
